# AI Review & Generation Prompts — Stage 1 through Stage 7

Built for **Claude Code** (or an equivalent agent with filesystem/repo access). Covers generation steps (Stage 2-Draft, Stage 3-Implement) and review steps (Stage 1, 2a–2d, 3 review, 3-Security, 3-Infra, 4–7) across the full workflow. Each prompt assumes the agent can read the repository, run search/grep, and read existing docs (Confluence exports, ADRs, schema files) if you point it at them.

**How to use these:**
- Drop the relevant prompt into Claude Code at the matching stage, with the ticket/Design Doc link filled in.
- Every prompt ends with a **required output format** — keep that, so findings can be pasted straight into Jira/Confluence and stay consistent reviewer-to-reviewer.
- Every prompt includes a grounding instruction (don't speculate, read the actual files) — this is what makes the difference between a real review and a generic one.
- Stage 2 has two parts: **Stage 2-Draft generates** the Design Doc, **Stage 2a/2b/2c/2d review and plan** against it (architecture, NFRs, data model, and test strategy respectively). The architect is accountable for the final design either way — the draft just removes the blank-page problem and front-loads the codebase research.
- **Stage 2d (Test Strategy)** decides *what kind* of testing this change needs — and at what pyramid layer — before implementation starts. This exists precisely because "write tests" left implicit defaults to thin unit-test coverage and skips the cross-service contract tests that actually catch the failures this whole workflow is designed to prevent.
- **Stage 3 has three review angles, run as separate sessions from the implementing agent and from each other:** correctness/design-conformance (Stage 3 review), security at the code level (Stage 3-Security — distinct from Stage 2's design-level security sign-off, since secure designs can still have insecure implementations), and infrastructure/IaC where applicable (Stage 3-Infra). None of these substitute for the human merge gate — they're evidence the human approver uses, not the approval itself.

