### Notes on using these with Claude Code

- These assume the agent is pointed at a checked-out copy of the repo (or repos, for cross-service checks) — give it the actual paths, don't paste code snippets when the agent can read the files itself.
- For Stage 1 and Stage 2c specifically, if your services live in separate repos, the agent needs access to all of them to find cross-repo dependencies — a single-repo view will systematically under-report exactly the risk this stage exists to catch.
- Treat the "confidence" and evidence-citation requirements in these prompts as non-negotiable — an agent with repo access that doesn't show its file/line evidence is indistinguishable from one that's speculating, and you lose the entire reason for giving it codebase access.
- These are a starting point per the Anthropic prompting guidance: pair them with a `CLAUDE.md` at your repo root describing your architecture/conventions, so every agent invocation has that context without you repeating it in each prompt.
- Before running any of these against real code, confirm the agent's runtime can't reach production credentials or real customer data — see §4.5 (AI Agent Access Boundaries) in the main workflow document. This matters more here than it would for a generic coding assistant, since these prompts are explicitly designed to give the agent broad read access across services.
- None of the review prompts above are a substitute for the human merge gate (workflow doc, Stage 3) — they produce evidence a human approver uses, the same way a linter or CI check does, not an approval in themselves.
